rever there=E2=80=99s a microphone and a camera. It=E2=80=99s a national me=
dia blitz befitting a presidential campaign, but <em>wink wink</em>, Caruso=
 doesn=E2=80=99t hold any political office. He wants to help Los Angeles re=
build, and he has little faith that the city, county, and state can do it w=
ithout
the private sector expertise he=E2=80=99s bringing to the recovery effort. =
=E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99re past four weeks now, and very little has happened,=
=E2=80=9D Caruso told me by phone this week. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=80=99s just una=
cceptable.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><=
p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">Caruso=E2=80=94the billionaire prop=
erty developer, L.A. civic fixture, and French cuff devotee=E2=80=94has bee=
n making the media rounds to promote his nonprofit, Steadfast LA. It=E2=80=
=99s just one of several public-private partnerships launched
in the aftermath of the fires to =E2=80=9Cfight through bureaucratic delays=
=E2=80=9D and accelerate the rebuilding of Pacific Palisades, Malibu, Altad=
ena, and Pasadena with the help of other well-connected Angelenos, includin=
g Netflix chief <strong>Ted Sarandos </strong>and his philanthropist wife, =
<strong>Nicole Avant</strong>; Amazon=E2=80=99s <strong>Mike Hopkins</stron=
g>; and Palantir co-founder <strong>Joe Lonsdale</strong>. Caruso is Steadf=
ast LA=E2=80=99s chairman and is funding the effort himself, seeding it wit=
h
millions of dollars and promising to pressure local officials to get a move=
 on.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=
=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">On <em>Rogan</em>, Caruso basically said t=
he city is lucky to have him. =E2=80=9CI=E2=80=99ve got to help the leaders=
hip figure out how to be successful,=E2=80=9D he said. Rogan, who spent muc=
h of the episode bemoaning the state=E2=80=99s Democratic leadership, at on=
e point snidely referred to =E2=80=9Cthis woman=E2=80=9D running the city o=
f Los Angeles. That woman
would be <strong>Karen Bass</strong>, the beleaguered mayor who beat Caruso=
 for the job in 2022. Since the fires, it=E2=80=99s become abundantly clear=
 that Caruso wants a rematch, or maybe more.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin=
-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin:0;">Caruso is clearly passionate=
 about the recovery: He lives in the Palisades and developed the area=E2=80=
=99s signature (and still standing) shopping mall, and his daughter, <stron=
g>Gigi</strong>, lost her home in the blaze. But given his obvious
ambitions and near-daily media condemnations of Bass, it=E2=80=99s impossib=
le to talk to him about the fires and not <em>also</em> about his political=
 prospects. He told me he=E2=80=99s considering a run for governor of Calif=
ornia next year=E2=80=94which could set up a titanic showdown against <stro=
ng>Kamala Harris </strong>to lead the nation=E2=80=99s biggest state. =E2=
=80=9CEach of them is looking at the other,=E2=80=9D one Democratic consult=
ant told me. =E2=80=9CBut it=E2=80=99s got to be easy-ish. They=E2=80=99d b=
oth want to walk into that job. I can=E2=80=99t imagine
